Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| API | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption — wakes thread from `WaitOne()` | `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` via `WaitHandle.WaitAny` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop — forcibly kills `while(true)` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` + loop checks token |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call that must become cancellation-aware | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle })` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns the index of the signaled handle.
            // Index 0 = new event enqueued, index 1 = cancellation requested.
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (signaled == 1)
                break; // cancellation

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes a pre-existing race where
            // multiple Enqueue calls before the thread wakes would
            // leave items stranded after a single Dequeue).
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // signals token.WaitHandle, waking WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait for graceful exit
        // No Thread.Abort fallback — cooperative cancellation guarantees exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Original | Migrated | Reason |
|----------|----------|--------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Interrupt` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) and only works on `WaitSleepJoin` state. Cancelling the token signals `token.WaitHandle`, which `WaitAny` detects immediately. |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Removed entirely | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. The cooperative loop exits cleanly, so the fallback is unnecessary. |
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The loop must voluntarily check for cancellation — preemptive abort no longer exists. |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Makes the blocking wait cancellation-aware. Either a new event **or** a cancellation signal will wake the thread. |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` added | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` are `IDisposable`. Leaking them causes timer/callback leaks. |

## Key Pitfalls

1. **`WaitOne()` ignores cancellation** — Replacing `WaitOne` with `WaitAny` including `token.WaitHandle` is critical. Without this, `Cancel()` won't wake a blocked thread, and `Stop()` will hang for 5 seconds every time.

2. **`Thread.Abort` has no equivalent** — There is no way to forcibly kill a managed thread in .NET 8. If `Handle(item)` can hang indefinitely, you must also pass the `CancellationToken` into `Handle()` and check it there. If `Handle` calls uncooperative third-party code, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill`.

3. **Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — It allocates internal timers and registration lists. Wrap the class in `IDisposable`.

4. **Drain the queue, not just one item** — The original code had a latent bug: rapid `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` could strand items. The migrated version drains all items per wake-up.
